The paper discusses a framework for describing and composing Cyber-Physical systems, which involves computational and physical components and their interactions. This suggests that the paper could belong to several sub-categories, including Multi-Agent Systems (cs.MA), Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI), Robotics (cs.RO), Systems and Control (cs.SY), and Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO). However, since the paper focuses on agents with preferences, cs.MA and cs.AI are the most likely sub-categories. The use of Soft Constraint Automata also suggests a focus on modeling and reasoning about preferences, which further supports these sub-categories. The other sub-categories are still possible, but less likely based on the information provided in the abstract.
